<font color="#FF0000">TO ARTHUR &amp; TOM</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar 15 20:44:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Arthur,<br><br>
What you have told me about yourself surprises me.  Not that you have PTSD, but that you have alot of anger.  Of all the posts on this site, yours are refreshing and remarkable for their constant quality of being totally calm, cool, collected, and reasoned.  <br><br>
It takes alot of courage for you to disclose the things you have about yourself here.  It shows an amazing amount of trust.  Maybe you've already learned to trust more than you realize!<br><br>
I'm no psychologist, but I can't help offering my thoughts on anger.  I have worked through alot of anger and what helped me was to accept it, not resist it.  Allow yourself to be angry, and to express it, without feeling guilty.  You deserve to be angry.  Get in touch with it, and express it. Of course you don't want to misdirect the anger at the wrong targets, but go easy on yourself if you do.  It has to come out sooner or later, and the more you get it out, the sooner your soul will reach equilibrium.  Maybe it's time you expressed some anger on this site.  Why not lay into Doc Spatz.  That guy always seems to be looking for a fight.  I can't believe some of the things he's said on this site (like his post on #44 about medals).  It looks to me like that guy is going around poking at your guys' wounds, trying to see what kind of reaction he can get.  There would be an appropriate target for your anger. ;-)  Hey, don't listen to me about this stuff though, what do I know?  Just my thoughts.<br><br>
I'm glad that I've been able to give you a different perspective, from somebody who was not involved in the debate at all back then.  Somebody who has learned about the Vietnam War exclusively after the fact, mostly from hearing people talk about it, movies, maybe some TV shows.  I agree that the mind sees the world in from two different perspectives: the emotional one and the intellectual.  I've found the intellectual one is the one to be trusted most often.  I'm really glad that you can see, at least from an intellectual perspective, that Vietnam Vets are no longer looked down upon or scorned in any way in our society. <br><br>
Tom,<br><br>
Thanks for your support of my ideals.  It's so frustrating and depressing to be told ideals of disarmament and world peace are foolish or naiive.<br><br>
I think you are 100% right on with your thoughts on the Gulf War.<br>

